SIMPLE: epitaph
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Epitaph
<hw>Ep"i*taph</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>⟦eacute⟧pitaphe</ets>, L. <ets>epitaphium</ets> a funeral oration,
fr. Gr. <?/, orig. an adj., over or at a tomb; <grk>'epi`</grk> upon +
<?/ tomb. Cf. <er>Cenotaph</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An inscription
on, or at, a tomb, or a grave, in memory or commendation of the one
buried there; a sepulchral inscription.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hang her an <qex>epitaph</qex> upon her tomb.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A brief writing formed as if to be inscribed on a
monument, as that concerning Alexander: ⟦ldquo⟧Sufficit huic tumulus,
cui non sufficeret orbis.⟦rdquo⟧</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Epitaph</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Epitaph
<hw>Ep"i*taph</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To commemorate by an
epitaph.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let me be <qex>epitaphed</qex> the inventor of English
hexameters.</q> <rj><qau>G. Harvey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Epitaph</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Epitaph
<hw>Ep"i*taph</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To write or speak after the
manner of an epitaph.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The common in their speeches <qex>epitaph</qex> upon him . . .
⟦ldquo⟧He lived as a wolf and died as a dog.⟦rdquo⟧</q> <rj><qau>Bp.
Hall.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Epitapher</ent>⟦br⟧
